1/ The Bitcoin ETFs are going to need A LOT of BTC. But:
1. Where will the BTC come from?
2. And is there enough BTC to go around?

I spent my morning reading ETF applications trying to figure this out...
2/ The overwhelming majority of ETF applicants chose Coinbase Custody as their Custodian (hodlr). In every case where Coinbase is the custodian, they're also the Prime Execution Agent (trader).

3/ Coinbase routes trades through their "Connected Trading Venue" which according to Blackrock's S-1:

"currently include Bitstamp, LMAX, Kraken, the platform operated by the Prime Execution Agent, as well as four additional non-bank market makers (NBMMs)"

4/ "The Prime Execution Agent has represented to the Trust that it is unable to name the NBMMs due to confidentiality restrictions."

So the sources of BTC are exchanges and 4 shadowy whales? Interesting...

5/ The filing goes on to say, "the Prime Execution Agent may have an incentive to favor its own interests and the interests of its affiliates over the Trust‚Äôs interests."

So likely the BTC will come from wherever Coinbase earns the highest fees.

6/ But do exchanges have enough BTC on the books to fulfill ETF purchases?

Not even close! The TOTAL number of bitcoins for sale across all those exchanges (today, at any price!) is:
Coinbase: 3,191
Kraken: 1,520
Bitstamp: 555
LMAX: 318
Total = 5,584

7/ At $50k * 5,584 that's $279,200,000. Bitwise announced that they have an investor ready to buy $200 Million on DAY ONE. And apparently Black Rock has $2 BILLION https://news.bitcoin.com/bitwise-plans-to-seed-spot-bitcoin-etf-with-200-million-sec-filing-shows/
8/ So where will the Bitcoin for the ETFs come from? Coinbase, other exchanges, and shadowy whales. And will there be enough BTC to go around? Not at $50k, that's fer sure...
